Russia says it is expecting a “solid package of proposals” from African governments and businesses at the Russia-Africa Summit which is starting tomorrow, in Sochi, Russia. The summit follows Moscow’s few years of concentrated diplomatic, economic and military push as it seeks to deepen ties with the continent. Dozens of African leaders, including President Muhammadu Buhari, are expected at the top-level meeting, which will be co-chaired by Russian President, Vladimir Putin, and Egypt’s Abdel Fattah el-Sisi. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY Putin told the state news agency, TASS, that Russia had a lot to offer “our African friends” and that details would be discussed at the summit. He said the summit was to build a fair partnership relations based on equality and mutual practical interest. On the new scramble for Africa, Putin said Russia had no intent to “participate in a new ‘re-partition’ of the continent’s wealth” but to engage in competition for cooperation in compliance with the law. Russia-Africa summit: Moscow wants 'solid package of proposals' from Nigeria,others Buhari arrives Sochi ahead of Russia – Africa Economic Summit Spurned by Washington, North Korea’s Kim seeks a friend in Putin